ce:section.ce:para:
There are reports in the literature that the luminescence properties of CDs are affected by many factors, so we comprehensively studied the effects of reaction temperature, feedstock amount, and reaction time on the fluorescence of CDs. As shown in Figure S1a, we adjusted the reaction temperature and feedstock amount and found that there was no apparent red shift or blue shift in the position of the emission peak, but the fluorescence intensity was quite different. At 180℃, the ratio of GSH : PPD was 1 : 1, the fluorescence intensity is the strongest. We also studied the effect of reaction time on the product. Through the graph of TEM, we found that when the reaction time is 30 min, as shown in Figure S2a, the product is not entirely carbonized and appears in the form of polymer particles with an average particle size of 15.8 ± 1.3 nm (Figure S2b). As shown in Figure S2c, increasing the reaction time to 60 min, the product still exists in the form of an incompletely carbonized polymer with a particle size of 11.3 ± 1.8 nm (Figure S2d). When the reaction time increased to 90 min, the TEM graph was shown in Fig. 1
                        b, particle size of the product is 3.9 ± 0.4 nm (Fig. 1c). This is because as the reaction time increases, the raw materials gradually carbonized to form CDs. When the reaction time continues to increase to 2 h, as shown in Figure S2e, the product will excessively carbonize and exist in the form of carbon particles with a particle size of 23.0 ± 2.9 nm (Figure S2f). According to the above experimental results, the synthesis conditions of the CDs used in the experiment were as follows: the ratio of reactants GSH : PPD = 1 : 1 (GSH 0.334 g, OPD 0.118 g), and the reaction time was 90 min at 180℃ (Scheme 2
                        ).
